I"<p>Do you ever find yourself a few commits into trouble on an important branch like <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">master</code>? I know I do (and just did).</p>

<p>One way to turn back the clock is to run <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git log</code>, find the commit code for where things were OK, and then run <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git checkout -b recover bfc6c06</code>. Youâ€™ll get a new branch called <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">recover</code> to collect yourself. Then you probably want to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git branch -D master</code> then, from the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">recover</code> branch, run <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git checkout -b master</code> to start a fresh <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">master</code> branch from the good <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">recover</code> branch.</p>
